AB  - During the last fifty years, urbanization was one of the key processes which altered the European landscape significantly. Currently, the process of population, industry and commerce concentration in the core city changes to a process of de-concentration in the course of suburbanization. This phenomenon known as urban sprawl has recently expanded across most European agglomerations. Urban sprawl takes place on condition of liberal market constraints, thus it is difficult to monitor and cannot be reconciled easily with the urban planning concept of “decentralized concentration”. Hence the dispersion phenomenon of urban patterns is becoming an important topic in applied remote sensing research, as shown in the surveys of Kasanko et al. (2006) and Schwarz (2010). Both studies compare European cities regarding their spatial structure and temporal dynamic on the basis of CORINE Land Cover (CLC) data and in addition with socioeconomic statistics and landscape metrics. In the comparative analysis presented here urban growth modeling is carried out for cities differing in compactness and/or the extent of urban sprawl. The results are compared with the previous work carried out by Kasanko et al. (2006) and Schwarz (2010). Based on CLC data, the urban growth model SLEUTH (Clarke et al., 1998), which is based on the technology of cellular automata, is parameterized for two selective European cities. Cellular automata are able to simulate the complexity and the dynamics of urban systems adequately with quite simple methods. The SLEUTH-model has been applied in multiple studies in particular for North American agglomerations. By applying a modified version of SLEUTH it is possible to reduce the necessary data for calibration from four to two historical land use data sets, which makes the model suitable for the use of CLC data. In detail the following research questions are addressed: 1) how far will the dispersion of selected European cities progress until 2030, 2) how far will a similar trend arrive for presently compact cities, implying “business-as-usual” constraints, and 3) is the application of the SLEUTH urban growth model for European cities as suitable as for North American cities?
